## Examples

### Example 1: E-Commerce Platform

```
Input: "Design backend for e-commerce platform targeting 1M users, $50K budget"

Architect Agent Output:
1. System Architecture Diagram (Mermaid)
   ├─ API Gateway + Load Balancer
   ├─ Authentication Service
   ├─ Product Service (with search)
   ├─ Order Service (async payment)
   ├─ PostgreSQL (products, users, orders)
   ├─ Redis (cache, sessions, cart)
   ├─ RabbitMQ (async tasks)
   └─ CDN (images, static assets)

2. Component Design
   ├─ API Gateway: Rate limiting, request logging, routing
   ├─ Product Service: 3 instances, Redis cache, search index
   ├─ Order Service: 2 instances, async payment processing
   ├─ Database: Master-slave replication, read replicas
   └─ Cache: Redis cluster, 13GB total

3. Data Flow Documentation
   ├─ Browse flow: Client → API → Product Service → Cache/DB
   ├─ Checkout flow: Client → Order Service → Payment Worker → Stripe
   ├─ Inventory update: Stripe webhook → Queue → Inventory Service

4. API Specification (OpenAPI)
   ├─ GET /api/products (paginated, searchable)
   ├─ POST /api/orders (create order)
   ├─ POST /api/orders/:id/pay (process payment)
   └─ 20 endpoints total with full schema

5. Database Schema
   ├─ users table with email unique index
   ├─ products table with category index, full-text search
   ├─ orders table partitioned by month
   ├─ order_items table with foreign keys
   └─ 15+ indices optimized for query patterns

6. Caching Strategy
   ├─ HTTP cache: Products (1h), Cart (no-cache)
   ├─ CDN cache: Images, static assets
   ├─ Redis cache: Products, search results, sessions
   └─ Cache invalidation: Event-driven on updates

7. Implementation Code
   ├─ API Gateway (Express with middleware)
   ├─ Product Service (with caching logic)
   ├─ Order Service (with transaction handling)
   ├─ Event handlers (RabbitMQ subscribers)
   └─ Database queries (parameterized, indexed)

8. Scalability Analysis
   ├─ Capacity: 1M users, 500 RPS peak
   ├─ Database: 500GB, sharding strategy at 5M users
   ├─ Infrastructure: 20 servers at 1M users, $5K/month
   └─ Growth timeline: Launch → 3mo → 6mo → 12mo projections

9. Deployment Guide
   ├─ Docker configuration for each service
   ├─ Kubernetes manifests with resource limits
   ├─ Monitoring (Prometheus, Grafana)
   ├─ Logging (ELK stack)
   └─ Rollout strategy (rolling updates, blue-green)
```

### Example 2: Real-Time Chat System

```
Input: "Design backend for real-time chat app, 100K concurrent users"

Architect Agent Output:
1. Architecture Diagram
   ├─ WebSocket server (Socket.io, 10 instances)
   ├─ Message Service (async, persistent)
   ├─ User Service (profiles, presence)
   ├─ Redis (message cache, user presence, pub/sub)
   ├─ PostgreSQL (messages, users, conversations)
   ├─ Elasticsearch (message search)
   └─ Kafka (message queue for search indexing)

2. Data Flow
   ├─ User connects: Browser → WebSocket → Presence Service → Redis
   ├─ Send message: Browser → WebSocket → Message Service → Postgres + Kafka
   ├─ Search: Browser → Search API → Elasticsearch
   ├─ Real-time delivery: Kafka → WebSocket servers → Browser

3. API Design
   ├─ WebSocket endpoints: connect, send_message, typing, ...
   ├─ REST endpoints: GET /conversations, POST /messages/search
   └─ Full OpenAPI spec

4. Database Schema
   ├─ users: id, name, avatar
   ├─ conversations: id, created_at, participants
   ├─ messages: id, conversation_id, sender_id, content, timestamp
   ├─ presence: user_id, status, last_seen (in Redis)
   └─ Indices on conversation_id, sender_id, timestamp

5. Caching Strategy
   ├─ User presence: Redis with auto-expiry
   ├─ Recent messages: Redis cache (last 100 per conversation)
   ├─ Typing indicators: Redis pub/sub

6. Implementation Code
   ├─ WebSocket server with authentication
   ├─ Message service with persistence
   ├─ Presence tracking service
   └─ Event handlers for real-time updates

7. Scalability
   ├─ 100K concurrent users across 10 WebSocket servers
   ├─ 1M messages/day = 12 TPS average
   ├─ Database: Sharding by conversation_id
   ├─ Cache: Redis cluster with 100GB memory

8. Deployment
   ├─ Stateless WebSocket servers (Kubernetes)
   ├─ Load balanced by connection hash
   ├─ Health checks for connection draining on restart
```

